reviewText: As the WWF would be forcibly renamed WWE later on in the year, this is the last Royal Rumble for the WWF, but also the last great one.WWF Tag Team ChampionshipThe Dudley Boys vs Tazz and Spike Dudley (C)Added on in the extras was Tazz and Spike doing commentary on their match, a definite highlight as Tazz is great in the commentary.  The match itself was as long as it needed to be, with enough action to keep the audience interested and not complaining for tables like they usually do later on.  Spike suffers a bit (not literally) as he does the Dudley Dog three times instead of anything else.  (7/10)Edge vs William RegalOnce again, Regal fails to impress in a very dull effort livened up a bit by Edge.  I have no idea what the booking was going for here, but Regal was hardly a technically sound wrestler, or a classic Greco-Roman style here.  (3/10)WWF Women's ChampionshipTrish Stratus (C) vs JazzTypical women's match for the WWF, which is to say little that can impress compared to a men's match.  (4/10)Vince McMahon vs Ric FlairIn my opinion, this match went three or four minutes too long, as it started out incredibly boring with Vince showing off what a high protein and GHB diet can do for a man in his late 50s, and Lawler can't stop wetting his pants because of it.  Then the pace picked up as both began to dominate one another in what some people call a "classic" street fight.  It wasn't that good for me.  (6/10)WWF Undisputed ChampionshipChris Jericho (C) vs The RockPhenoms that Jericho and The Rock are, I'm ashamed that I expected nothing much from them.  Instead they put on a great WWF wrestling match, with little flair (not Ric) and style, and just a grunginess accentuated by their personalities which made it great.  (9/10)Royal Rumble MatchNot perfect, or as great as the 2000 and 2001 Rumbles, this one was nonetheless greatly executed, with regular intervals in the match creating for a non-stop bash that felt like several matches in one, from Goldust and Rikishi's bout, to the Undertaker dominating, getting eliminated by Maven, and proceeding to take Raven into a Hardcore-style beating all the way up into the concession stands, and Triple H and Stone Cold's brawl towards the end.  Very little in the match was actually boring.  (9.5/10)
summary: The last great Rumble of the WWF

reviewText: Tazz and Spike Dudley VS Dudley Boyz: I enjoyed this match but nothing memorable.William Regal VS Edge: The start of a long running feud. The match was alright with Regal using his famed brass knuckles to win the Intercontinental title.Trish Stratus VS Jazz: All my other wrestling reviews pretty much say what I think of women wrestling.Vince McMahon VS Ric Flair: A pretty good brawl but it lacked something. It was in Flair country and unlike WCW, Flair wins the match his famous figure four leg lock.Rock VS Jericho: This should have been a good match but I thought it was a little boring in the beginning. Towards the end things pick up, a highlight was Rock putting Jericho thru the spanish announce table with a rock bottom. Anyone else miss that table? The end saw the typical ref bump, Nick Patrick came in and refused to count The Rock's pin attempt, Rock hits a rock bottom on Patrick, and finally  Rock hit an exposed turnbuckle and Jericho rolled him up with his feet on the ropes for the win.Royal Rumble: This Rumble had alot of surprise returns, making it exciting. Under valued talent like DDP and Saturn make there apperances in the Rumble as well. I never watched WCW but i've always enjoyed DDP's work. He could have made a good world champion but WWF rather have the same old talent hold the world title. The big story going into the Rumble was Triple H's return to action. In the internet and smart fan age you can basically tell who the winner would be. The highlight was Maven dropkicking Undertaker over the top rope and eliminating him. 'Taker then destorys Maven thru the crowd and then throw's Maven face first thru a popcorn machine. If he is not offically eliminated then should he be declared the winner? Well, it's WWF/WWE and all logic should be put aside. A pretty good Rumble but the ending of course should have been known when Triple H returned a few agos on Raw and said he'd be in the Rumble.Overall, a decent PPV event. The first three matches were decent but things picked up quickly with Flair-McMahon. The title match was alright but not as exciting as I thought it could have been, considering the showmanship of both Jericho and Rock. The Rumble saw the returns of Mr. Perfect, Val Venis, and Goldust. 'Taker and Maven was a good highlight. When Triple H enters, it was over but Perfect did give it his all.

reviewText: The 2002 Royal Rumble was real exciting considering the fact that Triple H has returned to Pay Per View after being out for 8 months.  There was good and okay matches.  What was really good about this ppv was that there was no ordinary match.  Either there was a special kind of match or a title was on the line. Here are all the matches and how they were....#1 WWE Tag Team Championship: Tazz and Spike Dudley vs Dudley Boyz- Good tag team title match.  It was great for Spike because it was his first ppv where he defended a title and all though out of all 4 wrestlers he was the shrimp, but he put 110% in this match.#2 WWE Intercontinental Championship: Edge vs William Regal- an Okay.  Was exciting because a month before, Edge broke Regal's nose and everybody was proboly wondering what Regal had instore for Edge.  The only thing wrong was the end of the match.  It was dissapointing but the only way to know why is if you get this.#3 WWE Women's Championship: Trish Stratus vs Jazz-It was alright, the only thing that led to this match was Jazz winning a #1 contender spot for the title ...  What made the match exciting was that Jaqueline became a special guest ref and hated Jazz.#4 Street Fight: Vince McMahon vs Ric Flair- This owner vs owner match was really good, considering the fact of the men's age. Lots of brutality was in this match.#5 WWE Undisputed Championship: Chris Jericho (Y2J)vs The Rock- Ever since Jericho costed him and the rock a tag team match back in October against Shane McMahon & RVD, these have 2 been really going at it.  This was real good, there was little interfearence, lots of move countering,lot of suete moves happened such as the Rock rock-botttming Y2J from announce table to another!#6 Main Event: The Royal Rumble, consisted of 30 men:1. Rikishi 2. Goldust 3. Bossman 4. Bradshaw 5. Lance Storm 6. Al Snow 7. Billy Gunn 8. The Undetaker 9. Matt Hardy (with Lita)10. Jeff Hardy 11. Maven 12. Scotty 2 Hotty 13. Christian 14. DDP  15. Chuck 16. The Godfather 17. Albert 18. Perry Saturn 19. Steve Austin 20. Val Venis 21. Test 22. HHH 23. The Hurricane 24. Farooq 25. Mr. Perfect 26. Kurt Angle 27. Big Show 28. Kane 29. RVD 30. Booker TThis was one of the most excing ppv's ever.  Besides Triple H, there were other returns like Goldust, Mr. Perfect, Val Venis, and Godfather.  There was a lot of times where ot seemed some guys were gonna be eliminated but they managed not to.  The 2 most exciting things I thought were the best was Maven,the tough Enough champion, kicking Taker from behind and eliminating and Kane tossing big Show over the top rope.Overall this ppv is good to watch.  I gave 4 stars because there are some disapointments but it was still good.  Buy this.
summary: Triple h returns to Pay Per View

reviewText: This was pretty good, but not the best Royal Rumble.  The matches:Spike and Tazz vs Dudleyz with Stacy for the tag titles.  This was a pretty good match.  I thought it was pretty funny at one point Stacy went to slap Tazz but Tazz ducked and she go the tazzmission for a sec.  That was tight, lol.  Tazz and Spike barely retain the titles, after Tazz locks the tazzmission on d-von. **Edge vs Regal for IC title.  This match was ok, but their styles are pretty different, so the match aint the best. The main big pop i remember is Edge hittin a ddt on the apron.  Regal wins the IC title thanks to those brass knux(aahh!!) **Trish vs Jazz for women's title.  Nothin special in this match, Jazz runs most the match until Trish hits the bulldog to retain. *1/2Street Fight-Vince vs Flair.  This match was pretty aggressive, some blood from Ric of course.  Ric gains momentum at the end and wins with the Figure 4 Leg Lock. **1/2Undisputed title-Jericho vs The Rock.  This was an awesome match.  Jericho using the Rock Bottom, Jericho hittin two lionsaults, a sick rockbottom(from the rock) thru the announcer table, etc.  Jericho wins thanx to the exposed turnbuckle.  ****The Royal Rumble.  Some pretty shocking stuff in the Royal Rumble made it great.  The Hardyz returning to try and get revenge on Taker, Maven eliminating Taker(what a fan reaction), Kane actually picking Big Show up and dropping him over the top rope, etc.  4 ppl return to the WWE in the Royal Rumble: Goldust, Val Venis, Godfather(not good, god), and Mr. Perfect.  Triple H is the man as he wins the Royal Rumble and earns a shot at the title at WMX8.This Royal Rumble is good but not the best.  In my opinion Royal Rumble 2001 was probably the best thus far.  If u want my opinion on if u should buy this video or not, i'd say go ahead and buy it, unless u desperately want to rent it first.

reviewText: Here's my match reviews of the 2002 edition of the Royal Rumble.WWE Tag Team Championship:Tazz and Spike[c] vs Dudley Boyz**1/2Not too bad of a match, just an average match you could see on WWE TV but still a decent tag team match.WWE Intercontinental Championship:Edge[c] vs William Regal***1/2An amazing match by both competitors, lots of ground offense by Regal and high flying moves from Edge. This match ends in a controversial fashion with William Regal picking up the victory and becoming the new WWE Intercontinetal Champion.WWE Women's Championship:Trish Stratus[c] vs Jazz***A very good match with amazing action from both women. Definitley one of the best matches in the Women's Division.Street Fight Match:Ric Flair vs Vince McMahon****Both men are above the age of 50 and both delivered a tremedous match.(Although I still think that Flair's match at Wrestlemania X-8 was better) They gave it all they had and I was very suprised to see Vince and Flair take it to the next level.Undisputed WWE Championship:Chris Jericho vs The Rock****1/2This match was the best one on the card. This match defenitley topped their No Mercy confrontation as both superstars fought with a lot of match physcology and told a story. However, Jericho won with interference by Lance Storm and ChristianThe 30-Man Royal Rumble Match(To decide the number 1 contender for the Undisputed WWE Championship at Wrestlemania X-8)****The 2001 Rumble match was better in some areas. The beginning was a little boring but it immediately picked up in the middle when Steve Austin came in. The end was definitley the best part as Triple H, Booker T, Kane, Big Show, Kurt Angle, Mr. Perfect, Rob Van Dam, and Steve Austin battled it out to decide the winner, however, when the match was all said and done, Triple picked up the victory.
summary: Awesome Pay Per View and even better DVD extras!

reviewText: With the exception of the Royal Rumble from 1992 (where Ric Flair won the event and the WWF title along with it), this is probably my favorite version of the event! Let's get to it:Spike Dudley/TAZZ VS. The Dudley Boyz w/Stacy Kiebler (WWF/WWE Tag Team Championship) - Not a great bout but it doesn't suck either! Some very hard hitting spots that are very ECWsqe!Edge Vs. William Regal (WWF/WWE I-C Title Match) - Probably the only stinker on the card. Edge and Regal are actually very good workers but this one wasn't as good their other encounters.Trish Stratus Vs. Jazz (WWF/WWE Women's Title Match) - Surprisingly good match. Jazz is the superior wrestler and worker but I have to give Trish a lot of credit in that she does try her best in the ring! Also, having Jackie in there as the special ref added some comedy to the bout."Nature Boy" Ric Flair Vs. Vince McMahon (Streetfight Match) - This was also another surprise. McMahon and Flair worked very well together!Chris Jericho Vs. The Rock (WWF/WWE Undisputed Championship Match) - I have never seen their first encounter from No Mercy 2001 but if its anything like this match, then I am sure I'd love it! These two put on a great match! Probably the best between the two!The Royal Rumble Match - Was very well paced and probably the strongest line up since The Royal Rumble 1992! While it was pretty obvious that HHH was going to win, it at least gave us some great action leading up to that point. I find it ironic since the best Royal Rumble took place in 1992, that we get another great one 10 years later!This is a good DVD and a good card. Get it or at least rent it!

reviewText: WWFROYAL RUMBLE 2002This was a fun Rumble event right here as it was a fun time during the company. You would see the return of some superstars at this event for the Rumble including the big return of Triple H. also this was during the time when Vince was partners with Ric Flair which lead to so many great moments on Raw and Smackdown. You would see four title fights at this event plus a street fight between business partners and of course the Royal Rumble itself.1.[TAG TITLES]TAZZ & SPIKE DUDLEY VS THE DUDLEY BOYZ-really fun opening match in my opinion. I have read other reviews that say that this match was too short and that was the problem. Now I agree that the match was short but I don't think that it disappointed in any way. Big brothers really wanted to take it to Spike here over powering him at every turn. But Spike was resilient and Tazz as always was great with his suplexes. There is a lot of great action here and D Von tapping to the Tazzmission.2.[I-C TITLE]EDGE VS WILLIAM REGAL-we follow the tag match with a bout for the I-C title and like the first it was a good one. This one was more of a slower paced match but that was a good change in momentum. Some people don't like matches like that but some of my favorites have been like this. I like how the ref made sure [at least for a while] that Regal did not have his brass knucks. With that Edge went straight at him but Regal would work to keep the match grounded. In the end it was the returning brass knuckles that would lead Regal to victory.3.[WOMEN'S TITLE]TRISH STRATUS VS JAZZ-the next match and next title bout of the night would see the women go at it. This was at the time the typical women's match looking back now it was better than I thought at the time. Of course this match was really all about putting Jazz over without giving her the title. She dominates for most of the match only to lose to a Stratusfaction.4.[STREET FIGHT]RIC FLAIR VS VINCE MCMAHON-fun street fight here between these two that is very bloody. They brawl over the place and the taking turns taking pictures moments were great and funny. But despite Flair rightfully winning by making Vince tap to the figure four I didn't like how Vinnie mostly dominated the match. Flair is one of the greatest of all time and Vince can dominate him. The match doesn't suffer for it because Flair makes any one look good but still. Also this is the only non title match of the night.5.[WWF TITLE]CHRIS JERICHO VS THE ROCK-excellent match and best of the night in my opinion that is not the Rumble. The match that these two put on is great with Jericho trying everything he can to stay the undisputed champ. All the heel tactics you can think of happen here and Rock is in great form as well. Of course we all remember the rock bottom onto the announcers table which is just one great moment. I personally liked the ending here as it kept the belt on Jericho and still established him as a great heel. Y2J keeps the belt after a great back and forth match.6.[THE ROYAL RUMBLE]-now this was one of my favorite Rumbles of all time as it has everything a Rumble should. You have drama, action, and comedy all inside the ring. Also I like that there were people who returned here like Goldust, Val Venis, and The Godfather but it was Mr. Perfect that was so great to see back in action. Curt Henning [R.I.P.] like he always did in these matches shined and went all the way to the end. Had Kurt Angle not been in there with him I would have been all for him winning it. In fact when we were watching this on PPV that night they were the two I was rooting for. My favorite moment however was when Maven got the surprise elimination of the Undertaker. That was truly a great Rumble moment especially after Taker had cleaned house earlier in the match. Of course it would be the returning Triple H that would go on to win it. I remember being so mad that Kurt did not win this, he came ever so close and was the last eliminated so that is something I guess.Over all I would say this was one of the most fun Rumbles that I have watched. Every time I watch this event or one from this time period I think of Maryland as I lived there at the time. The DVD comes with interviews with the returning superstars, promos, Tazz & Spike reviewing their match, and of course Triple H's return on Raw. This was a really fun event like I said and I would recommend getting it if you can find it cheap enough.

reviewText: Royal Rumble lived up to the hype with the exception of a few bits. I won't be nasty like in my past reviews.Spike Dudley & Taz(z) (Tag Champs) vs. Dudley Boyz- This was a decent bout that only lasted four minutes. These guys could have gone at least 15 minutes longer though. All four were ECW veterans so you can't go wrong with this match!Rating-*** starsEdge vs. William Regal- These guys are great. I don't care what anyone says about Regal. He is one of the best workers in the WWE today. Regal dumps Edge right on the top of his head at one point in the match. It was the Sickest and Best Spot of the Night.Rating-**** stars for the intensityTrish Stratus vs Jazz- So-So for a woman's bout. Nothing much else to say. Jazz is a good worker.Rating- *1/2 starsVince McMahon vs. Ric Flair (No DQ)- Ric pulls off the first of two bloody, classic brawls in 2002. The Second being his match against Undertaker at WM 18. I understand that Vince is one of the worst sellers in the wrestling world but The Nature Boy is able to drag Vinnie Mac through a great brawl.Rating- ****1/2 StarsChris Jericho(WWF Champ) vs. The Rock- Not as good as their match at No Mercy 2001 which happened to win match of the year from several magazines, but it's still a good bout with tons of electricity.Rating- **** StarsRoyal Rumble Match- One of the better Rumbles. The 2001 Rumble match is way better than this one though. The top spot of the match has to be when Maven took his first chair-shot and did not even put his hands up. It was an intense shot too. Just as hard as Ian Rotten's chairshots in IWA Mid-South. I never thought Curt Henning would make it to the final three. That was his first and last shining moment in a while.Rating-***** Stars because it was all Action with only a few stalling spots. The match made 64 minutes seem like 20, and thats a good thing.-J.A.
summary: One of the Better WWF(E) Shows of 2002 So Far

reviewText: Royal Rumble 2002 was a very good PPV with some action packed undercard matches and one of the most star studded Rumble matches in years.1. Tazz & Spike Dudley vs. Dudley boys (WWF Tag Team Championship)Good way to kick off the show.  This was a ctually a pretty good tag match, just a little bit too short.  (8/10)2. Trish Stratus vs. Jazz (Women's Championship w/Jacqueline as Special Guest Referee)Not a bad woman's match, but who really cares.  (6/10)3. Edge vs. William Regal (Intercontinental)These two had a good fued, but the matches were just never that good.  Again, okay match, but nothing too special.  (7/10)4. Vince McMahon vs. Ric Flair (Street Fight)Good performance put on by these two old timers.  It is about what you would expect from these two.  Of course they both bleed pretty good.  There is a funny spot were Vince makes Flair's daughter take a picture of Vince and Ric with her camera.  (8/10)5. The Rock vs. Chris Jericho (Undisputed Title)This has to be one of the most underrated matches of the year.  You never hear much about this match.  It is action packed from beginning to end.  There are many close falls and a great announce table to announce table bump.  Surprise appearance by Christian adn Lance Storm. Ggreat match.  (9/10)6. Royal Rumble Match (Wineer Gets A Shot at Undisputed Title at Wrestlemania 18)This Rumble match featured one of the best fields in years.  Some of the highlights include Maven eliminating The Undertaker and Taker proceeding to destroy Maven all over the arena, the Triple H and Austin stare down, the return of Goldust, Val Venis, The Godfather, Mr. Perfect, and Perfect being one of the final four participants left in the ring.  Good ending, but a little too predictable.  (9/10)Overall the PPV was pretty good.  It has a great championship match and Rumble match.  It would be a good addition to your DVD collection.Overall Rating:  8.5/10

reviewText: ok here is a spoiler free review just to refresh your memory and help you remember if you want to get Rumble 2002:Opening match, Tazz and Spike defend the tag titles against Dvon and Bubba, A good match although a little short in my opinion.Next up Edge takes on William regal with his IC title on the line, for Regals standards this match was ok.Trish Stratus (oh yeah) vs Jazz with Jackie as Ref... a pretty good match... but could have been better.Vince Mcmahon vs Ric Flair: great street fight considering the age of both the men.Y2J vs The Rock for the unified world title, A great match, Strong offence from both men will definetly keep your interest.And of course the main event the royal rumble... 30 men and in my opinion one of the best Rumble matches of all time... here is the list of competitors in alphabetical order:Al Snow Albert Big Show Billy Booker T Big Bossman Bradshaw Christian Chuck Dallas Page Faarooq Godfather Goldust Jeff Hardy Kane Kurt Angle Lance Storm Matt Hardy Maven Mr. Perfect Perry Saturn Rikishi Rob Van Dam Scotty Too Hotty Steve Austin Test The Hurricane Triple H Undertaker Val Venis.With the extra features the WWF always includes in Royal Rumble dvd's this one will no doubt be an essential for any true fans collection!
summary: All in all another great WWF PPV.

reviewText: Great way to start off 2002! This was a great Rumble. I won't get into each match, as other people already did that. What I can tell you is that the matches are great. I loved the bloody Street fight, but the clincher here is the actual Royal Rumble itself. This had to be one of THE BEST Royal Rumble matches in a long time. The best moment is with Maven sending the Undertaker over the top. I firmly believe that, that 1 moment will forever define the amount of success he gets. Great Superstar with a lot of potential.This DVD is well worth it, the extras aren't bad either, but I would have liked to have seen exclusive footage of past Royal Rumble winners or something. The WWF does no wrong. "God Bless Vince McMahon"
summary: Great 1st DVD of the new year!

reviewText: The 2002 edition of the Royal Rumble was personally the greatest Rumble I'd ever seen, having watched it last night on PPV.  Even the last 2 Rumbles don't come to par with this one.  The matches are soo intense and action packed that you will be watching it over and over again.  Matches include:-Tag Team Championship: Dudleyz vs. Tazz+Spike Dudley(champs)-Intercontinental Championship: William Regal vs. Edge(champ)-Women's Championship: Jazz vs. Trish(champ) w/ Jackie as special referee-Street Fight: Vince McMahon vs. Ric Flair-Undisputed WWF Championship: The Rock vs. Chris Jericho(champ)-Royal Rumble: the winner goes on to WrestleMania 18 to fight in the main event for the Undisputed Championship.
summary: The best Royal Rumble ever, period!

reviewText: I expected alot from the 2002 Royal Rumble, but I really dont know why. I really enjoyed the main event, and one or two other matches, but there was nothing stellar here.Tazz (C) and Spike Dudley (C) vs. the DudleysThis match could have been better, but it was way too short. These four guys can put on a solid tag match given the right time. Still, it was decent, and about what I expected.Edge (C) vs. William RegalThis was a very good match, but again, way too short. Edge and Regal are very capable wrestlers and put on a good (and bloody) show. Edge shows alot of promise here, and its no surprise that he's become a big player in the WWE.Trish Stratus (c) vs. Jazz with Jacqueline as the Special RefereeTrish can put on good matches, but she and Jazz were only given three minutes to work. Granted, Jazz wasnt much of a wrestler anyway. I had hoped for more, but again, I was disappointed.Ric Flair vs. Vince McMahon in a Street FightI rather liked this match. Flair proves he can still take a beating, and Vince looked better than I could have hoped. Unfortunately, the match was all blood and violence, and Flair didnt get to showcase his true wrestling talent.Chris Jericho (C) vs. the RockOverrated as he is, the Rock can put on some decent matches when given a good wrestler to work with, and Jericho is an excellent wrestler. This is one of the few matches of the night that didnt disappoint. Perhaps not the duos greatest match, its still worth a watch.2002 Royal Rumble MatchThe main event started off slow, and really only got interested when Steve Austin entered the ring. Triple H made his return, and much to my delight, so did Mr. Perfect, Curt Hennig. Once the match got down to the final four (Steve Austin, Kurt Angle, Triple H, and Hennig) this match got to be VERY good. These four guys put on one hell of a show. And the best part is, the four of them got to go at it for about 10 minutes, as the match itself clocked in at 69 minutes. A predictable ending couldnt put a damper on this one.Its hard to recommend this show, because the undercard is pretty weak, and the Rumble only picked up in the last half hour. If you can, watch the Rumble though. Mr. Perfect proves he can still wrestle 8 or 9 years after he got out of the came, and its hard not to get a little nostalgic when you get to see the now late Curt Hennig exchange blows with the biggest stars of the time.

reviewText: Revisiting the 2002 "Royal Rumble" has been one of the strangest experiences of my life.  Every match I liked when I first saw it is now very fun today, and matches that bored me really entertain me.  What the hell happened?  I dunno, but the bottom line is that I think this is one of 2002's weaker PPVs.1) Tag Team ChampionshipsThe Dudley Boyz v. Tazz & Spike Dudley (champions)---Tazz and Spike?!  I know you can't judge a wrestler by his size, but that's a strange combo for someone who didn't see these guys much when I watched them in ECW.  Anyway, this is curtain jerker that doesn't do anything outside the box.  It moves fast.  There's a few crazy bumps here and there.  Cue the hot tag for the fresh, ready good guy.  Match is over.  Sorry if I spoiled the formula for you, but so many tag team PPV openers take no chances.  And am I really supposed to believe that Spike Dudley can take on a man as large as Bubba Ray, or even D-Von?  Is this a bad match?  No.  Is it anything special?  No.  Will it be over before you know it?  Probably."5.5 / 10"-------------------------------------2) Intercontinental ChampionshipEdge (champion) v. William Regal---Man, I used to hate watching these two guys work together.  I thought, "It's so slow, they're not doing anything!"  Ah, but years later, I realize they are.  They're trying to have a more believable match where two guys look like they're trying to win a match.  Edge takes some more high-risk offense, while Regal looks for the dirty way to gain his advantage.  Nowadays, I love watching these guys work together.  I won't call this a Match-of-the-Year candidate, but I think anyone will enjoy the suspense involving Regal's brass knuckles that keep finding their way into his matches.  I'd put this one above their prior "Vengeance 2001" encounter, but not quite as good as their "No Way Out 2002" showdown 1 month later."7.0 / 10"-------------------------------------3) Women's ChampionshipSpecial Referee - JacquelineJazz vs. Trish Stratus (champion)---I think this one needs to be put in some perspective.  Trish was still learning her way around the ring (by her own admission), while Jazz was one of the fiercest women the WWF had ever seen.  This match is decent while it lasts, but it only lasts about 6 minutes.  Considering the Women's belt had only been reinstated for a few months, and considering how the unique dynamic Trish & Jazz had, I thought --- even back in 2002 --- we deserved more.  But while it lasts, it's entertaining enough."5.5 / 10"-------------------------------------4) Street FightRic Flair (WWF Co-Owner) v. Vince McMahon (WWF Co-Owner)---The theme of my review seems to be, "If I loved it, I don't anymore.  If I didn't like it, I really do now."  This Street Fight used to be so much fun for me.  The first time Flair stepped back into a WWF ring.  The rules were thrown out the window.  The evil, greedy Vince McMahon had to share his company after survivng the WCW/ECW Invasion.  The match gets bloody, goes all over ringside, and proved someone as old as Flair or Vince could still perform.  This used to be a very fun match for me.  But then some years passed, and I saw footage of Flair's old NWA classics, and then did some reading about Flair's personal life, and I thought, "Wow!  This Street Fight really doesn't show what Ric Flair can do."  Think about this: Flair used to battle legends like Ricky Steamboat and Dusty Rhodes for 60 minutes, yet was getting beaten around like a rookie by Vince McMahon.  To the fan who enjoys to research wrestling history, this Street Fight doesn't really work anymore.  Maybe Flair's fans or Vince's fans won't share my criticisms, but I think Ric Flair really outdid himself later in 2002 against the likes of Eddie Guerrero and Chris Jericho.  I don't hate this match, but I find it to be a little too ridiculous."5.5 / 10"-------------------------------------5) Undisputed WWF ChampionshipThe Rock v. Chris Jericho (champion)---I used to be bored by this match.  I also used to be an idiot [insert obvious joke here].  How in the holy hell did I find this match boring?  I think I was so offput by this storyline, that I wasn't willing to enjoy.  If you watch the pre-match video, you see Jericho crying like a baby, begging The Rock to respect him, even though he'd already beaten him TWICE on North American PPV!  This man had become the first-ever to defeat The Rock AND 'Stone Cold' Steve Austin on the same night.  Why was this talented wrestler acting like such a crybaby?  While I think the storyline is still a bit weak, the match itself is anything but.  These guys could do just about anything together.  They could wrestle slow.  They could fight hard and fast.  They could both talk a good game.  I also think that years ago, I was predicting that The Rock would finally get his PPV win over Y2J, and was getting bored with Jericho dominating (even though I wanted him to win).  But times have changed, and I've changed.  It is so much more difficult for wrestlers to compete in a style that demands a fan's patience, rather than giving into the quick-and-easy spots.  The Rock and Chris Jericho have such strong chemistry that patient fans (which I wasn't) will be rewarded with a match that could end at any moment.  There's a reason that this match is on The Rock's 3-disc set.  It's because any match where Jericho and The Rock square off is a good one."8.5 / 10"-------------------------------------6) 30-Man Royal Rumble---And my revisit of tonight's 3-hour PPV takes an even weirder turn, as my once-favorite Rumble is now one my least favorite.  How did that happen?  Well, years ago, I'd become tired of 30-Man Royal Rumbles that had a bunch of guys piling up, and not really doing anything except lift-attempts that never worked.  This 2002 Rumble, in many ways, was a game-changer.  The whole match moves so fast that it's hard to get bored.  But now as I rewatch this Rumble, that fast pace is precisely the problem.  It goes so fast that guys just get eliminated left and right without really getting to do a whole lot.  There are some great moments of course, with Undertaker's shocking elimination being the best (even Taker fans had to applaud the bold surprise).  This Rumble also makes a huge mistake by putting all of the likely winners in the final 9 entrants, or so.  Halfway through the Rumble, the superstars that got the most TV hype hadn't even shown up yet.  In fact, the one participant who makes the best impression is Mr. Perfect, and he was one of the 4 mystery participants!  I personally never had a problem with Triple H winning the Rumble, because his comeback story was as well-hyped as Steve Austin's possible 4th Rumble win or Kurt Angle's short career clearing another obstacle.  But in hindsight, perhaps it was a bit too easy.  Like most of this PPV, I don't hate this 30-Man Royal Rumble.  But when I revisit older AND newer Rumbles, this one simply moves so fast that you never get the chance to really enjoy it."5.5 / 10"-------------------------------------OVERALLAlright, I admit it.  This is a strange review.  I've basically told you how I now dislike a PPV that I used to love.  Well, people change, and their tastes along with it.  I simply don't like this "Royal Rumble 2002" as much as I used to.  The opening Tag Titles Match is by-the-numbers, the Women's Title Match is way too short, the Street Fight is too unbelievable, and the 30-Man Royal Rumble is way too fast.  Ironically, I really dig the Edge/Rgal and Rock/Jericho matches that used to bore me years ago.I dunno, take this review for what it is.A comparison against my high-school memories.
summary: The Mind Can Play Dirty Tricks

reviewText: I just finished watching this PPV a few hours ago, and to tell u the truth I was rather dissappointed, heres why. The only matches of any interest were Flair Vs. Mcmahon, Rock Vs. Jericho for the undisputed title, and the Royal Rumble match itself.Flair Vs. Mr. Mcmahon- what a dissappointment...Flair was so out of shape my guinea pig is in better shape than him...anyways Vince was buff, he kicked flair's ass all match and finally 20 minutes threw Flair actually did something and locked the figure four leg lock on Vince, and Vince tapped out, like it or not, Mcmahon realy should have won.Next Rock Vs. Y2J for the undisputed title-Gimme a break..This match was a rematch of No mercy's match and it totally sucked, kind of short with a terrible ending...Match wasnt anything close to being good compared to No mercy's.Finally The Rumble match- I was really looking forward to this anyways but seeing how the past couple matchs blew i couldn't wait for it....and once again another match failed to deliver, In my view the whole match was pieced together poorly with Austin, HHH, Angle, Kane, Bigshow, and (Booker who?) lol, all comming out pretty much 1 after another. With the exception of the Undertaker who came out fairly early and never competed against Austin, HHH, etc...unstead he got eliminated by Maven! what? yes Maven! wtf is that. Were closing in on the end Austin, HHH, Angle, and of all ppl Mr. Perfect  are the 4 remaining. When it got down to these four i figured Perfect was long gone, but No! Austin gets eliminated first of the four by Perfect! Yes perfect....what what? Now is it just me or are the wwf script writers and Vince Mcmahon just taking craps and what ever comes out is the plot for what happens in wwf these days i mean cmon. Well it gets a little better, HHH does end up winning which was cool but i prefer Austin. Some highlights of the rumble match that were worth seeing is how badly austin opens a can for awhile he must have delivered at least 15 stunners to diff ppl, all in all bad PPV not horible...but bad. I highly doubt that with extras added to this DVD that it will even be worth buying dont waste your money...just rent it.
summary: Not horrible but certainly not the best rumble.

reviewText: I am doing a review of Royal Rumble 2002 and i use a grading system and each match gains a grade and at the end the total is divided by the matches to gain the percentage and the ratings for it  as followsGrading E- =0-6.66%E  =6.66-13.32%E+ =13.32-19.98%D- =19.98-26.64%D  =26.64-33.30%D+ =33.30-39.96%C- =39.96-46.62%C  =46.62-53.28%C+ =53.28-59.94%B- =59.94-66.60%B  =66.60-73.26%B+ =73.26-79.92%A- =79.92-86.58%A  =86.58-93.24%A+ = 93.24-100%Match One-Tag Team Championship-Tazz & Spike(C) Vs The Dudleys-Very short match to start the show off. Some good action and teamwork by these four men used. Give this match a little more time, a little more build up and make it more of a major match and you have yourself a great match. My rating 6.57/10.Match Two-Intercontinental Championship-Edge(C) Vs William Regal-This again was fairly short but longer then the opener. It had some good action and two good wrestlers who have had a good feud so far. This match didn't end this feud which continues as it didn't get the clean ending it needed to close it. My rating 5/10.Match Three-Womens Title-Trish Stratus(C) Vs Jazz-Special Referee Jacqueline-This match was an average match except it was about three minutes which is not long enough for a special referee title match. My rating 4/10.Match Four-Street Fight-Vince McMahon Vs Ric Flair-Solid match not to much technical stuff though but noone asked of that. This match told a story between two men who hate each others guts and want to kill each other. Gimmick matches have become overused and should only be used on special occasions when needed. My rating 6/10.Match Five-Undisputed Championship-Y2J(C) Vs The Rock-This may well not be as good as No Mercy 2001 or as good as Vengeance 2001 but damn hell this match wasn't bad. The only thing stopping this from being real good was the ending. The ending was cheap and pointless. My rating 7/10.Match Six-Main Event-Royal Rumble-This match had many surprises such as Maven eliminating the Undertaker, the Hardy Boys re-uniting, the Godfather, Val Venis and Mr Perfect returning and many more. This was the longest Rumble to date and it probably isn't the best as too many eliminations at once and people not lasting or making impact. My rating 5/10.The overall rating for this show is 33.57 out of 60 which is 55.95% which is equivalent to a C+. This show wasn't the greatest but it wasn't the worst. It just needed better matches at the start and better bookings needed to be made. Average start for the road to Wrestlemania.

No really though, this Royal rumbe like all others was action packed from beginning to end.  Very nice finish, kinda reminds me of HBK's win at the 1995 Royal Rumble.Rating:  Very Good

reviewText: The 2002 Royal Rumble was a pretty good PPV, but nothing to write home about. There was only one match that's really good, and that would be Jericho vs. The Rock.Tazz and Spike vs. The Dudleyz- ** Very average match. Why are all the other reviewers praising this. Decent, but nothing special.Edge vs. William Regal- ** Ugh. These two have no chemistry. In fact... I don't think William Regal has good chemistry with anyone. Honestly, this is simply a boring match with a few high spots and a [bad] ending.Trish vs. Jazz- ** A good women's match. Trish has really improved, and this was an enjoyable affair.Vince vs. Flair- * Horrible match. Vince just kicked the [heck] out of Flair with non wrestling moves for fifteen minutes before Flair locked Vince in the figure four. Trust me- You'll be fast forwarding through this one.The Rock vs. Jericho- **** Great match- Exciting, well done, and very entertaining. Not quite on par with their amazing match at No Mercy, but better than their one at Vengeance. Very cool table spot.Royal Rumble- *** Extremely predictable, but nontheless enjoyable. Fun to watch, and exciting to watch live, but once its all over, not very re-watchable. GO Triple H!Well there you have it- a decent PPV to kick off 2002, but nothing amazing- only worth owning if you're a collector.

reviewText: Royal Rumble 2002 was not as good as 2001 or 2000, but it is without a doubt the second best one out of the past three years. The Undisputed title match was awsome when Jericho put his title on the line against the rock and the rumble match really shined in some places.The Dudley Boyz vs. Tazz and Spike: Pretty good opener, but I was expecting a lot more. Tazz and Spike really didn't make a good tag team in my opinion, but they had to be in a match somewhere, so why not make them a tag team. A good opener, but not the best. 7.5/10Jazz vs. Trish Stratus: Not as good as the women's matches nowadays, and Jazz vs. Trish is just a match that I have seen too much of, don't watch this. 6/10Edge vs. William Regal: Someone should have killed this rivalry before it even started. I was bored out of my mind in this one. These two are talented in their own ways, but just can't put on a good show together. Another boring match! 7/10Ric Flair vs. Mr. McMahon: Good God, what did I do to make the wwe mad enough at me to make this match for me to waste my money on? Only one good moment in this match, when McMahon brought Flair to his kids at ringside and told his daughter to take a picture of Flair when he was bleeding. 6/10Chris Jericho vs. The Rock: Fiiiinally! The Rock has come back to save another ppv! This is a spectacular match! Jericho and the Rock really work well together. The match had near falls, exciting maneuvers, and a great table moment when the Rock Rock Bottomed Jericho throught the ENGLISH announce table instead of the SPANISH announce table! Imagine that, the Spanish announce table survives a title match! A great match. 10/10Royal Rumble: Excellent Royal Rumble, lots of big names like Angle, Austin, HHH, Undertaker, Mr. Perfect, and Kane. When Maven eliminated the Undertaker the Undertaker's face was hilarious! The chairshot that the Dead Man gave Maven after that was also eye-popping. When Austin and HHH were fighting and the hurricane came out and tried to chokeslam both of them was funny also. Stone Cold looked at HHH and said, "are you F#$%ing kidding me?" They then both eliminate Hurricane. I was dissapointed when Austin was eliminated, and when Triple H is alone with Angle, you could tell who was going to win. Some other great moments that I won't ruin. 10/10The last two matches that I talked about saved this ppv. Either than them the others are either bad, or okay everyonce in a while. Still, you should buy this ppv just for the Jericho, Rock match and the rumble.
